'''''Deepwater Horizon''''' was an ultra-deepwater, [[Dynamic positioning|dynamically positioned]], [[semi-submersible]] offshore [[Offshore drilling|drilling rig]]<ref name="rig spec2">{{cite web| url=http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/Deepwater-Horizon-56C17.html| title=Fleet Specifications: Deepwater Horizon| publisher=Transocean| accessdate=9 June 2010| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619121120/http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/Deepwater-Horizon-56C17.html| archivedate=19 June 2010| df=dmy-all}}</ref> owned by [[Transocean]]. Built in 2001 in [[South Korea]] by [[Hyundai Heavy Industries]],<ref name="mms ivan2">{{cite web | url=http://www.mms.gov/tarprojects/548/Ivan_FinalReport.pdf| title=Post Mortem Failure Assessment of MODUs During Hurricane Ivan| last=Malcolm Sharples ''et al'' for Offshore Risk & Technology Consulting Inc., under contract for [[Minerals Management Service]], Order no. 0105PO39221| date=April 2006| publisher=''[[Minerals Management Service|US Government Minerals Management Service]]'' -| pages=50–51| accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> the rig was commissioned by R&B Falcon (a later asset of Transocean),<ref name="merger2">{{cite news | url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=62234| title=Transocean Sedco Forex to close pending merger with R&B Falcon on January&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2001| date=29 January 2001| newspaper=PR Newswire| accessdate=23 June 2010}}  date of publication verifiable on http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-69685498.html</ref> registered in [[Majuro]], and leased to [[BP]] from 2001 until September 2013.<ref name="offshore-mag0111092">{{cite news | url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/index/article-display/6112303380/articles/offshore/volume-69/issue-11/departments/gulf-of_mexico/gulf-of_mexico.html| title=Deepwater Horizon contract extended| date=1 November 2009| work=Offshore Magazine| publisher=[[PennWell Corporation]]| accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> In September 2009, the rig drilled the deepest [[oil well]] in history at a vertical depth of {{convert|35050|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} and measured depth of {{convert|35055|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}<ref name="Transocean Release2">{{cite press release | title=Transocean's Ultra-Deepwater Semisubmersible Rig Deepwater Horizon Drills World's Deepest Oil and Gas Well| date=2 September 2009| publisher=Transocean| url=http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/IDeepwater-Horizon-i-Drills-Worlds-Deepest-Oil-and-Gas-Well-419C151.html| accessdate=7 June 2010| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100426171257/http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/IDeepwater-Horizon-i-Drills-Worlds-Deepest-Oil-and-Gas-Well-419C151.html| archivedate=26 April 2010}}</ref> in the [[Tiber Oil Field]] at [[Keathley Canyon]] block 102, approximately {{convert|250|mi}} southeast of [[Houston]], in {{convert|4132|ft}} of water.<ref name="rigzone200909022">{{cite news | url=http://www.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=79913| title=BP Makes Giant Deepwater Discovery with Tiber| date=2 September 2009| publisher=Rigzone| accessdate=29 June 2010}}</ref>

On 20 April 2010, while drilling at the [[Macondo Prospect]], an uncontrollable [[Blowout (well drilling)|blowout]] caused an [[Deepwater Horizon explosion|explosion on the rig]] that killed 11 crewmen and ignited a fireball visible from {{convert|40|mi}} away.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hazmatmag.com/issues/story.aspx?aid=1000370689| title=Understanding the initial Deepwater Horizon fire| last=Crittenden| first=Guy| date=10 May 2010| publisher=HazMat Management| accessdate=20 June 2010}}</ref> The fire was inextinguishable and, two days later, on 22 April, the ''Horizon'' sank, leaving the well gushing at the [[seabed]] and causing [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill|the largest oil spill in U.S. waters]].<ref name="largest in US hist2">{{cite news | url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2010-05-27-oil-spill-news_N.htm| title=Gulf oil spill now largest offshore spill in history as BP continues plug effort| date=27 May 2010| newspaper=USA Today| author=Staff and wire| accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref>

==Design==
[[File:Deepwater Nautilus.jpg|thumb|left|The ''Deepwater Nautilus'', sister rig to the ''Deepwater Horizon'' being transported aboard a [[heavy-lift ship]]]]
{{Deepwater Horizon oil spill series}}
''Deepwater Horizon'' was a fifth-generation, RBS-8D design (i.e. model type), deepwater, [[dynamic positioning|dynamically positioned]], column-stabilized,<ref name="mms ivan">{{cite web|last=Malcolm Sharples ''et al'' for Offshore Risk & Technology Consulting Inc., under contract for [[Minerals Management Service]], Order no. 0105PO39221|title=Post Mortem Failure Assessment of MODUs During Hurricane Ivan|url=http://www.mms.gov/tarprojects/548/Ivan_FinalReport.pdf|publisher=''[[Minerals Management Service|US Government Minerals Management Service]]'' - |pages=50–51|accessdate=23 June 2010|date=April 2006}}</ref> semi-submersible [[Offshore drilling|mobile offshore drilling unit]], designed to drill [[subsea]] wells for oil exploration and production using an {{convert|18.75|in|mm|abbr=on}}, {{convert|15000|psi|abbr=on}} [[blowout preventer]], and a {{convert|21|in|mm|abbr=on}} outside diameter [[marine riser]].<ref name="rig spec">{{cite web | url=http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/Deepwater-Horizon-56C17.html | title=Fleet Specifications: Deepwater Horizon | publisher=Transocean | accessdate=9 June 2010 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619121120/http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/Deepwater-Horizon-56C17.html | archivedate=19 June 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

''Deepwater Horizon'' was the second semi-submersible rig constructed of a class of two, although ''[[Deepwater Nautilus]]'', its predecessor, is not dynamically positioned.  The rig was {{convert|396|by|256|ft|abbr=on}} and capable of operating in waters up to {{convert|8000|ft|m}} deep, to a maximum drill depth of {{convert|30000|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name="rig spec" /> In 2010 it was one of approximately 200 deepwater offshore rigs capable of drilling in waters deeper than {{convert|5000|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=Rig Data Centre | url=http://www.rigzone.com/data | work=Rigzone | date=28 May 2010 | accessdate=28 May 2010}}</ref> Its [[American Bureau of Shipping]] (ABS) class notations were "A1, Column Stabilized Drilling Unit, AMS, ACCU, DPS-3".<ref name="mms ivan" />

In 2002, the rig was upgraded with "e-drill", a drill monitoring system whereby technical personnel based in [[Houston]], Texas, received [[Real-time computing|real-time]] drilling data from the rig and transmitted maintenance and troubleshooting information.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/index/article-display/161517/articles/offshore/volume-62/issue-11/news/general-interest/monitoring-system-reduces-rig-downtime.html|title=Monitoring system reduces rig downtime|date= 1 November 2002|publisher=[[PennWell Corporation]]|work=Offshore Magazine|accessdate= 22 April 2010}}</ref>

Advanced systems played a key role in the rig's operation, from pressure and drill monitoring technology, to automated shutoff systems<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.computerworlduk.com/news/it-business/20481/bp-oil-spill-slows-but-serious-it-failures-come-to-surface/|title=BP oil spill ‘slows’ but serious IT failures come to surface|date= 28 May 2010|publisher=Computerworld UK|work=IT news website|accessdate= 12 November 2010}}</ref> and modelling systems for [[Cementing equipment|cementing]]. The OptiCem cement modelling system, used by [[Halliburton]] in April 2010, played a crucial part in cement slurry mix and support decisions. These decisions became a focus for investigations into the explosion on the rig that month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.computerworlduk.com/news/it-business/3248321/deepwater-horizon-modelling-software-showed-bp-cement-conditions-unstable/|title=Deepwater Horizon modelling software showed BP cement conditions unstable|date= 12 November 2010|publisher=Computerworld UK|work=IT news website|accessdate= 12 November 2010}}</ref>

==History==

===Construction and ownership===
''Deepwater Horizon'' was built for R&B Falcon (which later became part of [[Transocean]])<ref name="merger">{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.co.uk/cgi/news/release?id=62234|title=Transocean Sedco Forex to close pending merger with R&B Falcon on January&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2001|date=29 January 2001|newspaper=PR Newswire|accessdate=23 June 2010}} - date of publication verifiable onhttp://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-69685498.html</ref> by [[Hyundai Heavy Industries]] in [[Ulsan]], South Korea.<ref name="mms ivan" /> Construction started in December 1998, the [[keel]] was laid on 21 March 2000,<ref name=abs>{{cite web | title=ABS Record: ''Deepwater Horizon'' | url=http://www.eagle.org/safenet/record/record_vesseldetailsprinparticular?Classno=0139290| publisher=American Bureau of Shipping | date=21 March 2000 | accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref> and the rig was delivered on 23 February 2001,<ref name=abs /> after the acquisition of R&B Falcon by Transocean.<ref name="marketwatch1">{{cite news| url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/transocean-ltd-provides-deepwater-horizon-update-2010-04-26 |title=Transocean Ltd. Provides Deepwater Horizon Update |date=26 April 2010 |newspaper=The Wallstreet Journal}}</ref>  Until 29 December 2004 the rig was registered in the Republic of Panama.<ref name=MHL>{{cite report | title = Deepwater Horizon Marine Casualty Investigation Report | date = 17 August 2011 | format = PDF | url= http://www.register-iri.com/forms/upload/Republic_of_the_Marshall_Islands_DEEPWATER_HORIZON_Marine_Casualty_Investigation_Report-Low_Resolution.pdf | publisher = Office of the Maritime Administrator |accessdate= 25 February 2013}}</ref>

Transocean, through its [[Steinhausen, Switzerland]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Entry for Triton Asset Leasing GmbH|url=http://www.moneyhouse.ch/en/u/triton_asset_leasing_gmbh_CH-170.4.009.095-7.htm|publisher=Moneyhouse.ch "Commercial register and company data"|accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> subsidiary<ref>{{cite web|title=Transocean Inc 10-K filings, Exhibit 21: Subsidiaries (SEC File 333-75899, Accession Number 1140361-7-4583)|url=http://www.secinfo.com/d12Pk6.u4f8.c.htm|publisher=SEC EDGAR  database, for the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=23 June 2010}}</ref> Triton Asset Leasing GmbH,<ref name=subsidiaries>{{cite web|url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/1568/145150510000023/filing-main.htm |title=Transocean Ltd., Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date Feb 24, 2010 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate =May 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name=abs /> operated the rig under the [[Marshall Islands|Marshallese]] [[flag of convenience]].<ref name=lease>{{cite news | first=Braden | last=Reddall | title=Transocean rig loss's financial impact mulled | date=22 April 2010 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN2211325420100422 | agency=[[Reuters]] | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> The rig was leased to BP on a 3-year contract for deployment in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] following construction.<ref>{{cite web|title=Deepwater Horizon launched by TSF|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/index/article-display/105846/articles/offshore/volume-61/issue-6/departments/vessels-rigsupgrade/deepwater-horizon-launched-by-tsf.html|publisher='Offshore'' magazine|accessdate=23 June 2010|date=1 June 2001}}</ref> The lease was renewed in 2004 for a year,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transocean Receives Contract Extensions for High-Specification Rigs Discoverer Enterprise and Deepwater Horizon.|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20040426006148/en/Transocean-Receives-Contract-Extensions-High-Specification-Rigs-Discoverer|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=23 June 2010|date=26 April 2004}}</ref> 2005 for 5 years,<ref>{{cite web|title=Transocean Inc. Announces Contract Awards for Two High-Specification Semisubmersible Rigs.|url=http://goliath.ecnext.com/coms2/gi_0199-4124320/Transocean-Inc-Announces-Contract-Awards.html|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|accessdate=23 June 2010|date=28 April 2005}}</ref> and 2009 for 3 years covering 2010 to 2013.<ref name="lease" /><ref name="offshore-mag011109">{{cite news|url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/index/article-display/6112303380/articles/offshore/volume-69/issue-11/departments/gulf-of_mexico/gulf-of_mexico.html|title=Deepwater Horizon contract extended|date= 1 November 2009|publisher=[[PennWell Corporation]]|work=Offshore Magazine|accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref>  The last contract was worth $544&nbsp;million, or $496,800 a day,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/business/6672098.html | title=The Well |date= 17 October 2009| work=The Houston Chronicle |accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref> for a "bare rig",<ref name="forensic">{{cite web|author1=Bartley J. Eckhardt, PE  |author2=Arthur Faherty|title=Forensic Anatomy of the Events on the Deepwater Horizon|url=http://www.robsonforensic.com/LibraryFiles/Articles/forensic-anatomy-of-deap-water-horizon.pdf|publisher=Robson Forensic|accessdate=23 June 2010|page=8|date=20 May 2010}}</ref> with crew, gear and support vessels estimated to cost the same.<ref name="forensic" />

According to R&B Falcon's filings to [[Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] in 2001, the transfer document between R&B Falcon and Transocean was dated 17 August 2001,<ref name="sec2001">{{cite web|url=http://edgar.secdatabase.com/2442/101540201502602/filing-main.htm |title=R&B FALCON CORP, Form 8-K, Current Report, Filing Date Aug 31, 2001 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate =May 15, 2018}}</ref> and the rig was specified as "official registration number of 29273-PEXT-1, IMO number of 8764597, with gross tonnage of 32,588 and net tonnage of 9,778"<ref name="sec2001" /> and the transfer value as {{nowrap|US $340 million}}.<ref name="sec2001" /> {{as of|2010}}, the rig was insured for {{Nowrap|US $560 million}} covering the replacement cost and wreckage removal.<ref name="marketwatch1" />

===Drilling operations===
''Deepwater Horizon'' worked on wells in the [[Atlantis Oil Field|Atlantis]] (BP 56%, [[BHP Billiton]] 44%) and [[Thunder Horse Oil Field|Thunder Horse]] (BP 75%, [[ExxonMobil]] 25%)<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idUKWLA495020080617| date=17 June 2008| title=BP's Thunder Horse starts oil and gas production| publisher=Reuters| accessdate=29 May 2009 | first=Tom | last=Bergin}}</ref> [[oil field]]s.  It was described at times as a "lucky" and "celebrated" rig,<ref name="mcclatchy" /> and in 2007 was still described as "one of the most powerful rigs in the world".<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaskida|url=https://news.google.com/archivesearch?q=%22One+of+the+most+powerful+rigs+in+the+world%22+deepwater+horizon&btnG=Search+Archives&num=100|publisher=Oil & Gas Investor|accessdate=23 June 2010|date=1 April 2007}} [http://www.alacrastore.com/storecontent/Business-and-Industry/162363344 Alternate link]</ref> In 2006 it discovered oil in the [[Kaskida oil field]], and in 2009 the "giant" [[Tiber oil field|Tiber field]].<ref name=Rigzone>{{cite press release|url=http://www.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=35730| title=BP & Partners Make Discovery at Kaskida Prospect in the Gulf of Mexico| publisher=[[Anadarko Petroleum]]| date=31 August 2006| accessdate=24 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=Discovery>{{cite press release |url=http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/IDeepwater-Horizon-i-Drills-Worlds-Deepest-Oil-and-Gas-Well-419C1.html?LayoutID=6 |title=Deepwater Horizon Drills World's Deepest Oil & Gas Well |date=2 September 2009 |publisher=TransOcean |accessdate=2 September 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100428004206/http://www.deepwater.com/fw/main/IDeepwater-Horizon-i-Drills-Worlds-Deepest-Oil-and-Gas-Well-419C1.html?LayoutID=6 |archivedate=28 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>  The well in the Tiber field has a vertical depth of {{convert|35050|ft|m|0|abbr=on}} and a measured depth of {{convert|35055|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}, below {{convert|4132|ft|abbr=on}} of water.<ref name=offshore/>  The well was the deepest oil well in the world,<ref name=Discovery/><ref name=offshore>{{cite news| url=http://www.offshore-mag.com/index/article-display/7488119241/articles/offshore/drilling-completion/us-gulf-of-mexico/2009/08/bp-drills__giant_.html| title=BP drills oil discovery in the Gulf of Mexico| publisher=[[PennWell Corporation]]| work=Offshore Magazine| date=2 September 2009| accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=reuters020909>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKN02119720090902| title=Transocean says well at BP discovery deepest ever| publisher=Reuters| author=Braden Reddall| date=2 September 2009| accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="Deepest">{{cite web|title=Transocean's Deepwater Horizon drills world's deepest oil and gas well |url=http://www.yourindustrynews.com/transocean%27s+deepwater+horizon+drills+world%27s+deepest+oil+and+gas+well_38385.html |publisher=Red Mist Media|accessdate=26 May 2010}}</ref> and more than {{convert|5000|ft}} further below the seabed than the rig's official drilling specification stated on the company's fleet list.<ref>{{cite web | title=Fleet Status Report | url=http://www.deepwater.com/_filelib/FileCabinet/fleetupdate/2010/RIGFLT-APR-2010.xls?FileName=RIGFLT-APR-2010.xls | publisher=Transocean | date=13 April 2010 | accessdate=9 June 2010}}</ref>

In February 2010, ''Deepwater Horizon'' commenced drilling an exploratory well at the Macondo Prospect ([[Mississippi Canyon]] Block 252), about {{convert|41|mi}} off the southeast coast of [[Louisiana]], at a water depth of approximately {{convert|5000|ft|m}}.<ref name="otMacondo">{{cite web|url=http://www.offshore-technology.com/projects/macondoprospect/|title=Macondo Prospect, Gulf of Mexico, USA|date=20 October 2005|publisher=offshore-technology.com|accessdate=9 May 2010}}</ref> The Macondo prospect exploration rights were acquired by BP in 2009,<ref name=auction>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomr.mms.gov/homepg/lsesale/206/cgom206.html|title=Central Gulf of Mexico Planning Area Lease Sale 206 Information|publisher=US Minerals Management Service| date= 8 August 2008 | accessdate= 6 June 2010}}</ref> with the prospect jointly owned by BP (65%), [[Anadarko Petroleum Corporation|Anadarko]] (25%) and [[Mitsui|MOEX Offshore 2007]] (10%).<ref name=subsea>{{cite web|url=http://www.subseaiq.com/Data/Project.aspx?project_Id=562|title= Offshore Field Development Projects: Macondo|publisher=Subsea.Org|accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> ''Deepwater Horizon'' was still working on the Macondo site on 20 April 2010, when a violent explosion occurred leading to destruction of the rig and resulting oil spill.<ref name=Rigzone2>{{cite news | url= http://www.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=91349 | title= Deepwater Horizon Still on Fire in GOM | publisher=Rigzone | date=21 April 2010 | accessdate=21 April 2010}}</ref><ref name="times sinks" /><ref name=BP>{{Cite press release | title=BP confirms that Transocean Ltd issued the following statement today | publisher=[[BP]] | date=21 April 2010 | url=http://www.bp.com/genericarticle.do?categoryId=2012968&contentId=7061443 | accessdate=21 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=92025 |title=Gibbs: Deepwater Horizon Aftermath Could Affect Next Lease Sale |publisher=Rigzone |date=30 April 2010 |accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> The well was in the final stages of completion at the time; its cement casing was injected and hardening, and the rig was due to move shortly to its next role as a semi-permanent production platform at the Tiber site followed by a return to the Kaskida field; squatting semi-permanently over an oil dome 50 miles off the coast of Louisiana.<ref name="mcclatchy">{{cite news|last=Washburn|first=Mark|title=A huff and boom ended Deepwater Horizon's good luck|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2010/05/14/94184/a-huff-and-boom-ended-deepwater.html|accessdate=18 June 2010|newspaper=''[[The McClatchy Company]]''|date=14 May 2010}}</ref> The exploratory work was described as "concluded" and permission had already been requested from MMS to terminate operations at the Macondo site.<ref>{{cite web|title=UPDATED: Search Continues for 11 Missing Workers|url=http://www.rigzone.com/news/article.asp?a_id=91349|publisher=RigZone|accessdate=19 July 2010|date=22 April 2010}}</ref>

During its operational lifetime, the rig was actively in operation for 93% of its working life (2,896 of 3,131 days). The remainder partly relates to time spent between sites.<ref name="AP rig record">{{cite news|title=Review: Oil rig inspections fell short of guidelines|url=http://www.timesnews.net/article.php?id=9023118|accessdate=24 June 2010|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=16 May 2010}}</ref>

=== Regulation, safety, and inspection ===
The [[Minerals Management Service]] (renamed on 18 June 2010 to the [[Bureau of Ocean Energy Management, Regulation and Enforcement]], or Bureau of Ocean Energy (BOE))<ref name="boe">{{cite web |url=http://www.mms.gov/ooc/press/2010/press0621.htm |title=Salazar Swears-In Michael R. Bromwich to Lead Bureau of Ocean Energy Management, Regulation and Enforcement |date=21 June 2010 |publisher=Bureau of Ocean Energy Management, Regulation and Enforcement |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626003005/http://www.mms.gov/ooc/press/2010/press0621.htm |archivedate=26 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> is the regulatory and inspecting body for offshore oil drilling and rigs in the [[United States of America]].<ref name="boe" /> According to an ''[[Associated Press]]'' investigation, certain safety documentation and emergency procedure information, including documentation for the exact incident that later occurred, was absent.<ref name="AP rig record" /> The exact number of required monthly inspections performed varied over time; the inspections were carried out as required for the first 40 months, but after that around 25% of inspections were omitted,<ref name="AP rig record" /> although the investigation notes this is partly expected, since there are circumstances such as weather and movement which preclude an inspection.<ref name="AP rig record" /> Reports of the last three inspections for 2010 were provided under [[Freedom of Information legislation]]. Each of these inspections had taken two hours or less.<ref name="AP rig record" />

During its lifetime the rig received 5 citations for non-compliance, 4 of which were in 2002 (safety, including the blowout preventer) and the other in 2003 (pollution).<ref name="AP rig record" /> A sixth citation in 2007 related to non-[[Ground (electricity)|grounded]] electrical equipment was later withdrawn when the equipment was determined to be compliant with regulations.<ref name="AP rig record" /> Overall the ''Deepwater Horizon''{{'s}} safety record was "strong" according to a drilling consultant reviewing the information.<ref name="AP rig record" /> In 2009 the Minerals Management Service "herald[ed] the Deepwater Horizon as an industry model for safety".<ref name="AP rig record" /> According to AP's investigation "its record was so exemplary, according to MMS officials, that the rig was never on inspectors' informal 'watch list' for problem rigs".<ref name="AP rig record" />

==Explosion and oil spill==
{{Main|Deepwater Horizon explosion|Deepwater Horizon oil spill}}
[[File:Deepwater Horizon offshore drilling unit on fire 2010.jpg|thumb|left|''Deepwater Horizon'' in flames after the explosion]]
{{Location map | USA
 | caption=Location of the ''Deepwater Horizon'' on {{nowrap|20 April 2010}}| label=DW Horizon
 | alt=site of the explosion | mark=<!--dot-->Red pog.svg
 | lat_deg=28.73667 | lon_deg= -88.38716
 | position=bottom |
}}
At {{Nowrap|9:45 P.M.}} [[Central Time Zone (Americas)|CDT]] on 20 April 2010, during the final phases of drilling the exploratory well at Macondo, a geyser of seawater erupted from the [[marine riser]] onto the rig, shooting {{convert|240|ft|abbr=on}} into the air.  This was soon followed by the eruption of a slushy combination of [[Drilling fluid|drilling mud]], [[methane gas]], and water. The gas component of the slushy material quickly transitioned into a fully gaseous state and then ignited into a series of explosions and then a firestorm. An attempt was made to activate the [[blowout preventer]], but it failed.<ref name=upstream290410>{{cite news | url=http://www.upstreamonline.com/live/article213497.ece | first1=Noah |last1=Brenner |first2=Anthony |last2=Guegel |first3=Rob |last3=Watts |first4=Anthea |last4=Pitt  | title=Horizon crew tried to activate BOP | newspaper=[[Upstream (newspaper)|Upstream Online]] | publisher=NHST Media Group | date=29 April 2010 | accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> The final defense to prevent an oil spill, a device known as a [[Blowout preventer#Types|blind shear ram]], was activated but failed to plug the well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/06/21/us/20100621-bop.html|title=Investigating the Cause of the Deepwater Horizon Blowout|date=21 June 2010|work=The New York Times}}</ref>

At the time of the explosion, there were 126&nbsp;crew on board; seven were employees of BP, 79 of Transocean, there were also employees of various other companies involved in the operation of the rig, including [[Anadarko Petroleum Corporation|Anadarko]], [[Halliburton]] and [[M-I SWACO]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Richard Pendlebury |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1287226/GULF-OIL-SPILL-Whys-BP-taking-blame.html |title=Daily Mail special investigation article: Why is BP taking ALL the blame? |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date=18 June 2010 |accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref> Eleven workers were presumed killed in the initial explosion. The rig was evacuated, with injured workers airlifted to medical facilities. After approximately 36 hours, ''Deepwater Horizon'' sank on 22 April 2010. The remains of the rig were located resting on the [[Seabed|seafloor]] approximately {{convert|5000|ft|abbr=on}} deep at that location, and about {{convert|1300|ft|abbr=on}} (quarter of a mile) northwest of the well.<ref name="times sinks">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/23/us/23rig.html | title=Oil Rig Sinks in the Gulf of Mexico|last1= Robertson|first1=Cambell| last2=Robbins| first2= Liz | date=22 April 2010 | work=The New York Times |accessdate= 22 April 2010}}</ref><ref name=bloomberg220410>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aHylLWhmGcI0 |title=Transocean Oil-Drilling Rig Sinks in Gulf of Mexico |work=Bloomberg |last1= Resnick-Ault|first1=Jessica |last2=Klimasinska| first2= Katarzyna |date=22 April 2010 |accessdate=22 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://response.restoration.noaa.gov/topic_subtopic_entry.php?RECORD_KEY%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=entry_id,subtopic_id,topic_id&entry_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=809&subtopic_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=2&topic_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=1 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429002721/http://response.restoration.noaa.gov/topic_subtopic_entry.php?RECORD_KEY%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=entry_id%2Csubtopic_id%2Ctopic_id&entry_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=809&subtopic_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=2&topic_id%28entry_subtopic_topic%29=1 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=29 April 2010 |title=Deepwater Horizon Incident, Gulf of Mexico |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]], [[Office of Response and Restoration]] |date=24 April 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref>

The [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill|resultant oil spill]] continued until 15 July when it was closed by a cap.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nwf.org/News-and-Magazines/National-Wildlife/Birds/Archives/2010/Oil-Spill-Birds.aspx | title=Bird Habitats Threatened by Oil Spill | date=30 April 2010 |work=National Wildlife |publisher=National Wildlife Federation | accessdate= 2 May 2010}}</ref>  [[Relief well]]s were used to permanently seal the well, which was declared "effectively dead" on 19 September 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nasdaq.com/aspx/stock-market-news-story.aspx?storyid=201009191214dowjonesdjonline000186&title=us-governmentdeepwater-horizon-well-is-effectively-dead|title=US Government: Deepwater Horizon Well Is Effectively Dead|accessdate=19 September 2009|date=19 September 2009}}</ref> 
{{Clear}}

==Aftermath ==
{{further|Deepwater Horizon litigation}}

Transocean received an early partial insurance settlement for total loss of the ''Deepwater Horizon'' of {{nowrap|US $401 million}} around 5 May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Green|first=Meg|title=Transocean: Insurers Have Already Paid $401&nbsp;Million for Deepwater Horizon Loss|url=http://insurancenewsnet.com/article.aspx?id=188498|publisher=Insurance news net|accessdate=17 June 2010|date=7 May 2010}}</ref> [[Financial analyst]]s noted that the insurance recovery was likely to outweigh the value of the rig (although not necessarily its replacement value) and any liabilities {{ndash}} the latter estimated at up to {{US$|200 million}}.<ref>{{cite news |last=Fortson |first=Danny |title=Rig firm’s $270m profit from deadly spill |url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/natural_resources/article7120655.ece| work=The Sunday Times |accessdate=17 June 2010|date=9 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref>

Litigation, ultimate roll call of damage, and the scope of final insurance recovery were all unknown {{as of|2010|06|lc=y}}, with analysts reporting that the aftermath was of unprecedented scale and complexity compared to previous disasters which themselves took many years to unfold and resolve.<ref name="reutersafrica">{{cite news|last=Stempel|first=Jonathan|title=Special Report - BP oil spill a gusher for lawyers|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE65T2HB20100630?sp=true|accessdate=19 July 2010|newspaper=Reuters Africa|date=30 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kam|first=Dara|title=Valdez expert: Psychological impact of Gulf oil spill won't fully emerge for years|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/valdez-expert-psychological-impact-of-gulf-oil-spill-776588.html|accessdate=19 July 2010|newspaper=palm Beach post news|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> A July 2010 analysis by the ''[[Financial Times]]'' on the aftermath cited legal sources as saying that "at some point the scale of [[Deepwater Horizon litigation|the litigation]] becomes so large that it really is novel", that "the situation is likely to be complicated further because the variety of probable cases means it will be hard to aggregate them into so-called [[class action]]s" and that there was "no way to put this in historical context because we have never faced anything like this before".<ref>{{cite news|title=BP: Eagles and vultures|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/2bf9db9e-8545-11df-9c2f-00144feabdc0.html|accessdate=19 July 2010|newspaper=''[[Financial Times]]''|date=1 July 2010}}</ref> As with the [[Exxon Valdez oil spill#Litigation and cleanup costs|Exxon Valdez disaster]], litigation was being discussed in terms of a 20-year timescale.<ref name="reutersafrica" />

In January 2013, Transocean agreed to pay US$1.4 billion for violations of the US Clean Water Act. BP had earlier agreed to pay $2.4 billion but faced additional penalties that could range from $5 billion to $20 billion.<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Science News | url = http://news.sciencemag.org/scienceinsider/2013/01/second-oil-spill-settlement-adds.html | author = David Malakoff | title = Second Oil Spill Settlement Adds to Gulf Coast Science and Restoration Funding | date = 3 January 2013 | accessdate= 2013-04-04}}</ref> In September 2014, Halliburton agreed to settle a large percentage of legal claims against them by paying $1.1 billion into a trust by way of three installments over two years.<ref name="HalliburtonDeepwater">{{cite news|title=Halliburton to pay around $1.1 bn for US oil spill claims|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/02/us-halliburton-settlement-macondo-idUSKBN0GX1DT20140902|date=2 September 2014|accessdate=3 September 2014|publisher=''Reuters''}}</ref> On 4 September 2014, U.S. District Judge [[Carl Barbier]] ruled BP was guilty of gross negligence and willful misconduct under the Clean Water Act (CWA). He described BP's actions as "reckless," while he said Transocean's and Halliburton's actions were "negligent." He apportioned 67% of the blame for the spill to BP, 30% to Transocean, and 3% to Halliburton. BP issued a statement strongly disagreeing with the finding, and saying the court's decision would be appealed.<ref name="BPverdict">{{cite news|title=BP found "grossly negligent' in Gulf of Mexico oil spill|url=http://www.neworleanssun.com/index.php/sid/225407625|date=4 September 2014|accessdate=5 September 2014|publisher=''New Orleans Sun''}}</ref>

On 8 December 2014, The US Supreme Court rejected BP's legal challenge to a compensation deal over the 2010 Gulf of Mexico oil spill.  The settlement agreement had no cap, but BP initially estimated that it would pay roughly $7.8bn (£6.1bn) to compensate victims.<ref name="BP loses latest US oil spill appeal">{{cite news|title=BP loses latest US oil spill appeal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-30375089|date=8 December 2014|publisher="BBC News"}}</ref>

