{{notability|date=November 2014}}
{{short description|gardening tool}}

A '''khurpa''' is a short handled cutting tool with a flat blade used for digging soil and [[weeding]] in small gardens or vegetable farms. It is commonly use in small farms or in ridges or rows of vegetables to [[Hoeing|hoewing]] or earth up the weeds.  It is used to cut branches of trees. It is traditionally used while in a [[squatting posture]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Surendra|first1=Singh|last2=Mittal|first2=J.P.|title=Energy in production agriculture|date=1992|publisher=Mittal Publications|location=New Delhi, India|isbn=8170994071|page=144|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rhN6q5c-6QUC&pg=PA144|accessdate=23 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Touba|first1=Jacquiline|last2=Glasser|first2=Barbara|title=Nepal : Chandra Bahadur Ale's painting "Simple living"|date=1997|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|location=New York|isbn=0823951030|page=24|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XbkPe_S-mnoC&pg=PT24}}</ref> Khurpa is word of [[Nepali language]]. 

It is in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] and other areas in India for various processes like tilling, bed preparation, weeding and digging at small scale.

